00:35:36.588 --> 00:35:38.150
JUDAH POLLACK: That sounds good.

00:35:38.150 --> 00:35:40.110
And so the more--

00:35:40.110 --> 00:35:42.380
the more your neurons
are closer to each other,

00:35:42.380 --> 00:35:43.530
the more they're wrapped
around each other,

00:35:43.530 --> 00:35:46.070
the more surface area they
can get into contact with--

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:48.620
kind of the way your genes
are wrapped up in a ball--

00:35:48.620 --> 00:35:51.330
the more chances there are
for the new connections.

00:35:51.330 --> 00:35:53.700
So that's why it can
improve what's going on.

00:35:53.700 --> 00:35:55.130
Again, your brain is structural.

00:35:55.130 --> 00:35:59.300
So as you as you strengthen
the structure of your brain,

00:35:59.300 --> 00:36:02.720
you strengthen your ability
to have these breakthroughs.

00:36:02.720 --> 00:36:06.470
And so while meditation is
ordinarily not an access point,

00:36:06.470 --> 00:36:09.140
it's a strengthening point, so
it's a plasticity strengthening

00:36:09.140 --> 00:36:10.340
point.

00:36:10.340 --> 00:36:13.790
The access points are
things like taking naps.

00:36:13.790 --> 00:36:16.520
Salvador Dali discovered the
power of the hypnogogic state,

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:18.320
when you're just falling
asleep and you're

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:20.750
in that liminal
in-between space.

00:36:20.750 --> 00:36:22.800
And other people have
discovered the hypnopompic,

00:36:22.800 --> 00:36:24.591
which is when you're
just coming out of it.

00:36:24.591 --> 00:36:27.020
When somebody says sleep
on it, that's a real thing.

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:29.210
Because when you go to
sleep, your default network

00:36:29.210 --> 00:36:31.501
starts working on things and
right as you're waking up,

00:36:31.501 --> 00:36:32.845
it tends to tell you things.

00:36:32.845 --> 00:36:34.970
And so in the book we talk
about Adam Cheyer, who's

00:36:34.970 --> 00:36:36.710
one of the co-founders of Siri.

00:36:36.710 --> 00:36:39.050
And this is just a
general practice of his.

00:36:39.050 --> 00:36:43.490
He goes to sleep, focuses on an
idea, specific problem he has,

00:36:43.490 --> 00:36:45.410
and that's using
his executive to say

00:36:45.410 --> 00:36:47.132
this is what we're
working on, and then

00:36:47.132 --> 00:36:48.590
he just allows this
default network

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:50.195
to do its thing at night.

00:36:50.195 --> 00:36:52.070
And then when he wakes
up, he kind of checks.

00:36:52.070 --> 00:36:53.990
He's like, what did it tell me?

00:36:53.990 --> 00:36:56.240
And it usually told him
something, he writes it down.

00:36:56.240 --> 00:36:57.770
He then gets up,
goes to his desk,

00:36:57.770 --> 00:36:59.750
goes back to his
executive network,

00:36:59.750 --> 00:37:01.460
and starts working it out.

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:03.020
And you see this
happen all the time.

00:37:03.020 --> 00:37:05.900
Einstein famously went
to his friend one day

00:37:05.900 --> 00:37:09.842
after 10 years in 1905, working
on his theories about light

00:37:09.842 --> 00:37:11.300
and simultanaeity
in time, and he's

00:37:11.300 --> 00:37:12.591
like, you know what, I give up.

00:37:12.591 --> 00:37:13.155
I'm done.

00:37:13.155 --> 00:37:14.780
And he went home,
and he went to sleep,

00:37:14.780 --> 00:37:16.509
and he wakes up, and voila.

00:37:16.509 --> 00:37:18.050
He comes back to
see his friend, he's

00:37:18.050 --> 00:37:19.942
like, I have it,
thank you so much.

00:37:19.942 --> 00:37:21.650
But here's the thing
about breakthroughs.

00:37:21.650 --> 00:37:22.280
That wasn't it.

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:25.820
He then spends six weeks
with his executive function

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:28.400
writing it all out,
getting it all straight.

00:37:28.400 --> 00:37:30.120
So there's this
constant back and forth,

00:37:30.120 --> 00:37:34.430
there's this interplay between
the two that is so important.

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:36.080
And so when you
access this mode,

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:38.900
you have to also remember to
use your executive to focus you

00:37:38.900 --> 00:37:40.374
on the issue at hand.

00:37:40.374 --> 00:37:42.290
To say OK, this is what
I want to think about,

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:43.550
this is what I'm going to do.

00:37:43.550 --> 00:37:44.929
Now I'm going to go take a walk.

00:37:44.929 --> 00:37:46.220
Now I'm going to go take a nap.

00:37:46.220 --> 00:37:47.512
Now I'm going to go for a swim.

00:37:47.512 --> 00:37:49.219
Now I'm just going to
sit in this hammock

00:37:49.219 --> 00:37:50.960
and let myself just
sort of wander off.

00:37:50.960 --> 00:37:52.835
Or I'm going to pick up this
book, but I'm not going to be--

00:37:52.835 --> 00:37:55.120
I'm not going to be focused
on like finishing the chapter.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:56.870
I'm just going to let
myself read the book

00:37:56.870 --> 00:38:00.440
and see if I kind of wander off,
see if something just comes out

00:38:00.440 --> 00:38:00.950
of it.

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:02.900
Or, if you're very
good at meditating,

00:38:02.900 --> 00:38:06.230
sit down for a 10,
20, 30 minutes sit.

00:38:06.230 --> 00:38:08.209
And then when you
come out of it say,

00:38:08.209 --> 00:38:09.500
I now want to think about this.

00:38:09.500 --> 00:38:11.660
Go for a walk, because
you've just sort of

00:38:11.660 --> 00:38:14.120
done an awesome workout
for your default network.

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:16.680
And it's sort of
primed and ready to go.

00:38:16.680 --> 00:38:20.900
And then you have to let go and
let it sort of do its thing.

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:23.780
One of the issues with accessing
it is because of the world

00:38:23.780 --> 00:38:25.140
we live in.

00:38:25.140 --> 00:38:28.706
We live in a world where we
are on task all the time.

00:38:28.706 --> 00:38:30.080
And one of the
interesting things

00:38:30.080 --> 00:38:33.010
is Douglas Rushkoff, an author,
has this fascinating concept

00:38:33.010 --> 00:38:35.990
where he said we have all this
technology, all these machines,

00:38:35.990 --> 00:38:37.520
and yet we're busier than ever.

00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:40.130
Weren't they supposed to
make our lives easier?

00:38:40.130 --> 00:38:41.300
Why is this?

00:38:41.300 --> 00:38:45.800
And his theory is that we have
internalized machine time.

00:38:45.800 --> 00:38:49.370
We actually operate at the pace
and rate of the machines that

00:38:49.370 --> 00:38:51.110
are supposed to be helping us.

00:38:51.110 --> 00:38:53.450
And so we answer emails
at all times of the night.

00:38:53.450 --> 00:38:54.980
We answer phone calls whenever.

00:38:54.980 --> 00:38:57.020
We're on constantly.

00:38:57.020 --> 00:38:58.970
And the problem with
being on constantly

00:38:58.970 --> 00:39:01.400
is you never access
your default mode.

00:39:01.400 --> 00:39:03.410
You never access
the genius lounge,

00:39:03.410 --> 00:39:05.060
and therefore you
never give yourself

00:39:05.060 --> 00:39:07.610
the chance to have
the brilliant ideas,

00:39:07.610 --> 00:39:09.590
to have the great breakthrough.

00:39:09.590 --> 00:39:12.470
The interesting thing is that
to have a true breakthrough,

00:39:12.470 --> 00:39:15.920
we need to pull back and
step into human time.

00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:19.940
We need to slow down, we need
to allow that pace to happen.

00:39:19.940 --> 00:39:22.800
We operate better when
we do that, we just

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:26.810
forget, get overwhelmed,
and then go, go, go, go, go.

00:39:26.810 --> 00:39:28.970
And it's not helpful.

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:31.060
So part of the
challenge with accessing

00:39:31.060 --> 00:39:34.710
this is allowing
yourself to slow down,

00:39:34.710 --> 00:39:39.340
is allowing yourself to
re-enter human time to do things

00:39:39.340 --> 00:39:43.140
like walk and nap and rest.

00:39:43.140 --> 00:39:44.010
Awe.

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:46.170
The experience of awe
is a wonderful way

00:39:46.170 --> 00:39:48.480
to access your network.

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:50.580
You just look up at
a picture like this,

00:39:50.580 --> 00:39:53.910
and the sheer immensity of
it all, and how small we are,

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:56.460
and we're aware of something
larger than ourselves.

00:39:56.460 --> 00:39:58.440
And the research shows we just--

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:00.690
we open up into a
whole different space.

00:40:00.690 --> 00:40:03.030
And we open up our brains
into a whole different space.

00:40:03.030 --> 00:40:05.040
And different connections occur.

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:08.160
Different parts of our brain
start talking, and we just--

00:40:08.160 --> 00:40:08.970
we're open to this.

00:40:08.970 --> 00:40:11.530
And this also
makes us slow down.

00:40:11.530 --> 00:40:13.260
You ever see anybody
just running along

00:40:13.260 --> 00:40:15.240
the rim of the Grand Canyon?

00:40:15.240 --> 00:40:17.250
When you come upon
something that produces awe,

00:40:17.250 --> 00:40:17.850
you slow down.

00:40:17.850 --> 00:40:21.840
When you walk up to a
Redwood, you slow down,

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:25.537
and you just kind of sit
there and say, my god.

00:40:25.537 --> 00:40:27.120
You don't even have
to believe in God,

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:29.130
and that kind of comes
out of your mouth

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:33.600
because we're just aware of this
larger entity in the universe.

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:37.860
And so go and look out, even
just looking out across the bay

00:40:37.860 --> 00:40:38.460
will do this.

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:42.180
So look out at the ocean, or
go up to the top of Mount Tam,

00:40:42.180 --> 00:40:44.400
and just look.

00:40:44.400 --> 00:40:47.100
The grand vistas will
ignite this in us,

00:40:47.100 --> 00:40:48.270
will bring it out of us.

00:40:51.986 --> 00:40:53.860
I want to talk a little
bit about constraints

00:40:53.860 --> 00:40:56.086
and the concept of wabi
sabi because constraints

00:40:56.086 --> 00:40:57.460
can be incredibly
helpful when it

00:40:57.460 --> 00:41:00.550
comes to accessing this sort
of breakthrough ability.

00:41:00.550 --> 00:41:02.770
Wabi sabi is this
Japanese design concept

00:41:02.770 --> 00:41:04.490
where you start with the flaw.

00:41:04.490 --> 00:41:07.180
The flaw is your zero
point, and you integrate it.

00:41:07.180 --> 00:41:08.680
The flaw is not to
be gotten rid of.

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:10.570
The flaw's not a
problem, the flaw

00:41:10.570 --> 00:41:14.020
actually directs the way in
which you're going to design.

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:16.590
And I love what street
artists do with this stuff.

00:41:16.590 --> 00:41:20.950
So a crack in the wall
becomes Spiderman's web,

00:41:20.950 --> 00:41:24.820
and a railing becomes fun
for Calvin and Hobbes.

00:41:24.820 --> 00:41:28.050
And this guy is
breaking out of jail.

00:41:28.050 --> 00:41:30.990
In this one they've turned the
breaking down of the plaster

00:41:30.990 --> 00:41:32.531
on the outside wall
into a factory,

00:41:32.531 --> 00:41:34.530
and it's the smoke coming
out of the smokestack.

00:41:34.530 --> 00:41:37.650
This kid's having a good time.

00:41:37.650 --> 00:41:41.400
And here we've got camels
making their way in a caravan.

00:41:41.400 --> 00:41:43.704
And all of this is
from they saw a flaw.

00:41:43.704 --> 00:41:45.120
Something was
wrong, and then they

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:48.960
used that to define how they
were going to create the art.

00:41:48.960 --> 00:41:51.472
And so the question becomes
what's the flaw in your system?

00:41:51.472 --> 00:41:52.680
What's your biggest obstacle?

00:41:52.680 --> 00:41:54.940
If you start from that
point, and not say,

00:41:54.940 --> 00:41:58.500
how do I get rid of it, but
say how is this my start point,

00:41:58.500 --> 00:42:02.910
it creates all kinds of creative
abilities, creative capacities.

00:42:02.910 --> 00:42:05.190
The flaw acts as sort
of the access point

00:42:05.190 --> 00:42:07.287
into your default network.

00:42:07.287 --> 00:42:09.870
And so one way you can do this,
and you can do this with teams

00:42:09.870 --> 00:42:11.612
as well, is you build
a constraint box.

00:42:11.612 --> 00:42:13.320
And we've found that
to be really useful.

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:15.030
We did this with Genentech
a little bit ago,

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:16.140
and it was very helpful.

00:42:16.140 --> 00:42:17.973
Because they were talking
about how annoying

00:42:17.973 --> 00:42:19.625
the federal regulations were.

00:42:19.625 --> 00:42:21.250
So we spun it around,
and we were like,

00:42:21.250 --> 00:42:22.590
we'll let's talk about
what are the constraints.

00:42:22.590 --> 00:42:24.798
And what you do you start
to lay out the constraints.

00:42:24.798 --> 00:42:27.480
Right, Dave is a
serious problem for me.

00:42:27.480 --> 00:42:28.930
So is the FDA.

00:42:28.930 --> 00:42:31.759
So is the cash flow, and
it's really not sexy,

00:42:31.759 --> 00:42:32.800
what we're talking about.

00:42:32.800 --> 00:42:34.870
It's going to be hard to get
anybody interested in it.

00:42:34.870 --> 00:42:36.090
So these are some
of your constraints.

00:42:36.090 --> 00:42:37.200
And you just get
a sense of them.

00:42:37.200 --> 00:42:39.270
You lay them out so they
don't get overwhelming.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:40.200
The next thing you
do is you start

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:41.790
talking about your assumptions.

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:43.890
Because very often you're
assuming things that

00:42:43.890 --> 00:42:45.227
aren't right, that aren't true.

00:42:45.227 --> 00:42:47.310
And if you don't write
them down and look at them,

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:49.740
they're just going to
stymie you the whole way.

00:42:49.740 --> 00:42:52.380
So, no one's going
to listen, Angela

00:42:52.380 --> 00:42:55.360
hates this idea, 18
months to see results.

00:42:55.360 --> 00:42:57.840
It's cost prohibitive, you
just lay it all out there.

00:42:57.840 --> 00:43:00.210
You look at it, and you
question all these assumptions.

00:43:00.210 --> 00:43:03.157
Are they really constraints
or are they just things

00:43:03.157 --> 00:43:03.990
that you've assumed?

00:43:03.990 --> 00:43:05.820
They're conversations
you haven't had.

00:43:05.820 --> 00:43:07.500
And the reason you
do it in this form

00:43:07.500 --> 00:43:08.916
is because what
happens in the end

00:43:08.916 --> 00:43:12.480
is this becomes
your solution space.

00:43:12.480 --> 00:43:14.920
You've now defined
where you can be free.

00:43:14.920 --> 00:43:17.430
You've defined the space where
your default network can now

00:43:17.430 --> 00:43:19.390
try any number of things.

00:43:19.390 --> 00:43:22.200
So as opposed to these things
hemming you in and locking you

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:25.420
in, they turn
around and free you.

00:43:25.420 --> 00:43:26.920
Because now you
know that you don't

00:43:26.920 --> 00:43:28.270
have to bother looking
at those things,

00:43:28.270 --> 00:43:30.353
you have to bother beating
your head against them,

00:43:30.353 --> 00:43:34.796
and now you've got this
space that's opened up.

00:43:34.796 --> 00:43:36.920
And that freedom is what
allows the default network

00:43:36.920 --> 00:43:39.002
to start to truly function.

00:43:39.002 --> 00:43:40.960
And so especially when
you do this with a team,

00:43:40.960 --> 00:43:42.504
it's amazing what
comes out and why.

00:43:42.504 --> 00:43:44.920
You start finding out that
there are all these assumptions

00:43:44.920 --> 00:43:46.300
on the table that
have stopped people

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:48.580
from getting interested in
things that weren't even

00:43:48.580 --> 00:43:50.770
correct in the first place.

00:43:50.770 --> 00:43:53.030
And little by little,
people start to realize,

00:43:53.030 --> 00:43:55.090
oh, but you know what we can
do, oh you know what we can do,

00:43:55.090 --> 00:43:57.460
and once you're in that space,
now your default network

00:43:57.460 --> 00:43:59.684
is live and functioning.

00:43:59.684 --> 00:44:01.600
And so this is one of
the ways the constraints

00:44:01.600 --> 00:44:04.690
can act as a really powerful
tool to get you into this.

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:08.380
Roman Mars of 99% Visible,
a really fun podcast,

00:44:08.380 --> 00:44:10.570
he has a great TED talk
talking about flags.

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:12.970
And he's like, you should
be able to draw your flag

00:44:12.970 --> 00:44:15.532
on a three by five note card.

00:44:15.532 --> 00:44:17.490
And everybody thinks it's
ridiculous and crazy,

00:44:17.490 --> 00:44:20.170
but he's like that's one of the
best constraints you can have,

00:44:20.170 --> 00:44:21.878
because it's going to
drive you to making

00:44:21.878 --> 00:44:22.930
a really excellent flag.

00:44:22.930 --> 00:44:25.138
And you can use that kind
of constraint and anything.

00:44:25.138 --> 00:44:27.330
Can you express it in a
three by five note card?

00:44:27.330 --> 00:44:30.310
Well then you probably don't
understand it well enough.

00:44:30.310 --> 00:44:31.077
Yes?

00:44:31.077 --> 00:44:33.304
AUDIENCE: Why do you call
it the default network?

00:44:33.304 --> 00:44:35.470
JUDAH POLLACK: Why do I
call it the default network?

00:44:35.470 --> 00:44:37.750
I don't, I'm quoting.

00:44:37.750 --> 00:44:41.860
When you're on task and doing
something, it goes more quiet.

00:44:41.860 --> 00:44:46.710
When you're off task, your
brain defaults to this network.

00:44:46.710 --> 00:44:48.770
It just-- this is where
it goes every time.

00:44:48.770 --> 00:44:51.040
So that's why it's called
the default mode network.

00:44:51.040 --> 00:44:52.990
And one of the funny
pieces is that the person

00:44:52.990 --> 00:44:57.985
who discovered it,
Dr. Marcus Raichle--

00:44:57.985 --> 00:44:58.485
how'd I do?

00:44:58.485 --> 00:45:00.450
OK, we'll leave it alone.

00:45:00.450 --> 00:45:01.950
The way he figured
it out was he was

00:45:01.950 --> 00:45:04.317
noticing that when he
had people in fMRIs,

00:45:04.317 --> 00:45:06.900
and told them to just hang on a
second, just wait, don't think

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:08.830
about anything, we have
to do something over here,

00:45:08.830 --> 00:45:10.110
all of a sudden all
this activity showed up

00:45:10.110 --> 00:45:10.800
in their brains.

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:12.210
And everyone was like,
oh it's just static,

00:45:12.210 --> 00:45:13.380
it's just noise, whatever.

00:45:13.380 --> 00:45:15.540
And then one day, he
walks out of a meeting,

00:45:15.540 --> 00:45:20.127
he's wandering down a hall,
and it just showed up.

00:45:20.127 --> 00:45:21.960
The idea showed up, and
so what happened was

00:45:21.960 --> 00:45:24.251
he was thinking about this,
he was thinking about this,

00:45:24.251 --> 00:45:26.180
and then when he was
off task, wandering down

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:29.250
a hall, his default network,
the brain defaulted to it,

00:45:29.250 --> 00:45:32.190
and then it gave him an answer
to a question he'd been asking.

00:45:32.190 --> 00:45:34.904
Which is what's up with
all this noise in the fMRI.

00:45:34.904 --> 00:45:35.820
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:37.310
JUDAH POLLACK: Yes.

00:45:37.310 --> 00:45:39.680
It's-- it's because it's this--

00:45:39.680 --> 00:45:42.474
it's this place where all
these different pieces

00:45:42.474 --> 00:45:44.390
are coming together and
talking to each other.

00:45:44.390 --> 00:45:44.960
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:46.070
JUDAH POLLACK: And--
right, and they're

00:45:46.070 --> 00:45:47.210
just sort of putting
things together.

00:45:47.210 --> 00:45:48.350
So we've discovered it.

00:45:48.350 --> 00:45:51.080
It truly is the engine
of our creativity.

00:45:51.080 --> 00:45:53.122
That's what we've been
starting to find out.

00:45:53.122 --> 00:45:55.580
And so these are all just ways
you can actually get into it

00:45:55.580 --> 00:45:57.025
and use it, focus
yourself on it.

00:45:57.025 --> 00:45:59.150
One of the things that--
we talked about this a lot

00:45:59.150 --> 00:46:00.649
in the beginning
of the book, can we

00:46:00.649 --> 00:46:01.970
give a kitchen recipe for this?

00:46:01.970 --> 00:46:07.220
Can we say one cup of
butter, two eggs, some sugar,

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:10.160
some chocolate chips, voila,
you'll have a breakthrough.

00:46:10.160 --> 00:46:11.650
And the answer is no.

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:15.920
It's a non-linear process;
it's an emergent process.

00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:18.704
And so you have to give
yourself time with it.

00:46:18.704 --> 00:46:20.870
But what we're teaching you
is that you can actually

00:46:20.870 --> 00:46:23.420
set conditions to make
it far more likely

00:46:23.420 --> 00:46:25.110
that it will happen.

00:46:25.110 --> 00:46:28.010
Switching, I want to
make a slight switch now

00:46:28.010 --> 00:46:29.930
to associative thinking,
which in the end

00:46:29.930 --> 00:46:31.992
is truly what your
default network is doing.

00:46:31.992 --> 00:46:34.450
And so I'm going to show you
something that will both raise

00:46:34.450 --> 00:46:38.540
your plasticity but also kind of
get into associative thinking.

00:46:38.540 --> 00:46:40.284
Somebody left their
Go Pro on the ground

00:46:40.284 --> 00:46:41.450
and a squirrel picked it up.

00:47:19.930 --> 00:47:21.730
So, I don't know about
you, but I'd never

00:47:21.730 --> 00:47:22.870
seen anything like that.

00:47:22.870 --> 00:47:26.530
That is literally a squirrel's
eye view of the world.

00:47:26.530 --> 00:47:28.040
And so it does a
couple of things.

00:47:28.040 --> 00:47:29.747
One, it forces this
growth of plasticity

00:47:29.747 --> 00:47:32.080
because you're like oh, my
god, it's like it's this big,

00:47:32.080 --> 00:47:33.820
and it's moving on branches
you could never move on,

00:47:33.820 --> 00:47:35.680
and it's moving so
quickly through the tree.

00:47:35.680 --> 00:47:37.388
I used to move through
trees very slowly.

00:47:37.388 --> 00:47:39.130
And all of this is
new and new and new.

00:47:39.130 --> 00:47:41.980
And then at the same time,
it adds to this piece

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:43.990
that we call
associative thinking.

00:47:43.990 --> 00:47:46.864
So all the media about
artificial intelligence

00:47:46.864 --> 00:47:49.280
and how it's going to replace
human beings and yadda yadda

00:47:49.280 --> 00:47:50.620
yadda.

00:47:50.620 --> 00:47:52.900
Most people who are
aware know that there's

00:47:52.900 --> 00:47:55.630
this big leap between where
AI is at the moment, which

00:47:55.630 --> 00:47:58.720
is amazingly good at the
pattern recognition and the data

00:47:58.720 --> 00:48:02.740
crunching, and the
intuitive, inferential leaps

00:48:02.740 --> 00:48:04.040
between ideas.

00:48:04.040 --> 00:48:06.040
And that's something that
human beings are still

00:48:06.040 --> 00:48:08.290
particularly good at.

00:48:08.290 --> 00:48:11.000
And it's the association
of the different ideas,

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.120
what's sometimes known
as abductive reasoning.

00:48:13.120 --> 00:48:14.530
To have a little
bit of data here

00:48:14.530 --> 00:48:17.170
and then to get a whole
theory out of it here.

00:48:17.170 --> 00:48:19.720
And this is what the default
mode network gives us.

00:48:19.720 --> 00:48:22.060
It is what takes
different pieces of data

00:48:22.060 --> 00:48:24.520
and puts them together into
a whole new conceptions,

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:25.990
whole new theories.

00:48:25.990 --> 00:48:29.290
And so having experiences that
are completely different--

00:48:29.290 --> 00:48:31.240
this gets at the hobby idea--

00:48:31.240 --> 00:48:34.000
brings in the ability to
create these associations

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.160
you might not ordinarily see.

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:39.440
So in the same way in
the 1970s San Francis--

00:48:39.440 --> 00:48:41.320
California, there was
a huge drought, people

00:48:41.320 --> 00:48:42.945
drained their swimming
pools, they just

00:48:42.945 --> 00:48:44.230
looked like empty holes.

00:48:44.230 --> 00:48:47.389
But a bunch of kids were
like, these are skateparks.

00:48:47.389 --> 00:48:49.930
That's something that comes up
from the default mode network.

00:48:49.930 --> 00:48:51.640
Or the skateboarding
kid who wants

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:53.500
to be able to keep
practicing in winter,

00:48:53.500 --> 00:48:57.910
so he creates a snowboard,
and invents snowboarding.

00:48:57.910 --> 00:49:01.270
Or the Army has got
Lexan, a hard plastic,

00:49:01.270 --> 00:49:03.430
that is used in
their windshields

00:49:03.430 --> 00:49:04.870
of their helicopters.

00:49:04.870 --> 00:49:07.660
And these windshields
are getting scratched up

00:49:07.660 --> 00:49:09.700
like nobody's business
in the deserts of Iraq

00:49:09.700 --> 00:49:11.440
and Afghanistan,
and in the training

00:49:11.440 --> 00:49:13.319
at Fort Irwin in California.

00:49:13.319 --> 00:49:14.860
And they're spending
tens of millions

00:49:14.860 --> 00:49:18.340
of dollars replacing
these Lexan, very

00:49:18.340 --> 00:49:19.900
scratchable windshields.

00:49:19.900 --> 00:49:22.480
And lo and behold, there are
these two Army Reserve National

00:49:22.480 --> 00:49:26.770
Reserve guardmen who are
helicopter mechanics and NASCAR

00:49:26.770 --> 00:49:27.790
fans.

00:49:27.790 --> 00:49:29.165
And they're like,
well, you know,

00:49:29.165 --> 00:49:31.330
NASCAR uses the same Lexan
on their windshields,

00:49:31.330 --> 00:49:34.420
but they put these thin
mylar sheets on top of them

00:49:34.420 --> 00:49:35.362
before every race.

00:49:35.362 --> 00:49:37.570
They're called tearaways,
and at the end of the race,

00:49:37.570 --> 00:49:38.590
they pull them off.

00:49:38.590 --> 00:49:40.450
The mylar took all the
hits and scratches,

00:49:40.450 --> 00:49:41.710
and the windshield's fine.

00:49:41.710 --> 00:49:44.110
But why don't we just put
them on the army helicopters?

00:49:44.110 --> 00:49:46.151
They took it from one
place, moved it to another,

00:49:46.151 --> 00:49:48.400
they associated it, saved
the Army tens of millions

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:50.860
of dollars because the
windshield's lifespan doubled

00:49:50.860 --> 00:49:51.880
and tripled.

00:49:51.880 --> 00:49:53.020
But it was already there.

00:49:53.020 --> 00:49:55.780
They associated it; they
moved it to another realm.

00:49:55.780 --> 00:49:58.150
And very often this
is how we end up

00:49:58.150 --> 00:49:59.500
seeing innovation happen.

00:49:59.500 --> 00:50:03.660
How many of you know of
Thomas Edison's electric pen?

00:50:03.660 --> 00:50:04.900
Exactly.

00:50:04.900 --> 00:50:08.070
He's not very proud of it
either, wasn't very successful.

00:50:08.070 --> 00:50:11.250
Ended up in the window of a
pawn shop, downtown New York.

00:50:11.250 --> 00:50:14.010
Who should be walking by but
this guy, Samuel O'Reilly.

00:50:14.010 --> 00:50:15.610
Samuel O'Reilly
takes a look at it,

00:50:15.610 --> 00:50:17.030
and he's a pretty clever guy.

00:50:17.030 --> 00:50:19.740
And he's like, I think I
could change this around.

00:50:19.740 --> 00:50:23.380
Samuel O'Reilly invents
modern tattooing

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:27.070
by changing the electric pen.

00:50:27.070 --> 00:50:30.200
Moving things in their context,
from one context to another,

00:50:30.200 --> 00:50:32.560
is very often where these
innovative ideas come from.

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:33.790
It's the association.

00:50:33.790 --> 00:50:35.290
And it's your default
network that's

00:50:35.290 --> 00:50:37.750
making those associations,
that's connecting,

00:50:37.750 --> 00:50:40.660
that's inferring, that's
intuiting between vastly

00:50:40.660 --> 00:50:41.390
different things.

00:50:45.600 --> 00:50:49.350
So there is a young
meteorologist--

00:50:49.350 --> 00:50:52.599
whose name I wrote
down, I can't remember.

00:50:52.599 --> 00:50:53.640
It's over here somewhere.

00:50:53.640 --> 00:50:54.750
I'll get it at the end.

00:50:54.750 --> 00:50:57.810
But he's up in the Arctic
in the early 1900s.

00:50:57.810 --> 00:51:00.930
And something just strikes
him, that the ice kind of looks

00:51:00.930 --> 00:51:02.670
like jigsaw puzzle pieces.

00:51:02.670 --> 00:51:03.310
And that's it.

00:51:03.310 --> 00:51:04.570
He just notices that.

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:06.710
It's interesting to him.

00:51:06.710 --> 00:51:08.390
A year later, he's
looking at a globe.

00:51:08.390 --> 00:51:11.100
He's like, huh, you
know, the continents kind

00:51:11.100 --> 00:51:13.230
of look like jigsaw pieces.

00:51:13.230 --> 00:51:15.450
I wonder if they
were ever together.

00:51:15.450 --> 00:51:18.060
And he goes, and he checks out
the rocks along South America

00:51:18.060 --> 00:51:19.260
and along Africa,
and he checks out

00:51:19.260 --> 00:51:20.801
some of the floor
and fauna, and he's

00:51:20.801 --> 00:51:22.890
like I think these
things drifted.

00:51:22.890 --> 00:51:24.900
He invented the concept
of continental drift,

00:51:24.900 --> 00:51:26.840
which eventually took
us to plate tectonics.

00:51:26.840 --> 00:51:29.250
A meteorologist
making a breakthrough

00:51:29.250 --> 00:51:31.260
in geology because
of an association

00:51:31.260 --> 00:51:34.500
he made by looking at
the ice in the Arctic.

00:51:34.500 --> 00:51:37.740
This is very often how it
works, this idea of curiosity,

00:51:37.740 --> 00:51:40.180
of noticing the way different
things come together.

00:51:40.180 --> 00:51:42.217
And it's the default
network, it's mindlessly

00:51:42.217 --> 00:51:43.800
staring out at the
ice and being like,

00:51:43.800 --> 00:51:45.420
huh, they look like
jigsaw puzzles.

00:51:45.420 --> 00:51:48.400
And then mindlessly staring
at a globe and being like,

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:51.810
oh, the jigsaw puzzles kind of
remind me of the continents.

00:51:51.810 --> 00:51:53.536
This is where these
things come together,

00:51:53.536 --> 00:51:54.660
and that's what I'm saying.

00:51:54.660 --> 00:51:56.310
It's important to
allow ourselves

00:51:56.310 --> 00:51:59.400
to be off task, because we
don't allow ourselves to access

00:51:59.400 --> 00:52:01.099
that network otherwise.

00:52:01.099 --> 00:52:02.640
So I want you to
imagine that gravity

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:05.340
stops working at 10 PM and
then starts working again

00:52:05.340 --> 00:52:07.400
at 7:00 AM.

00:52:07.400 --> 00:52:10.600
How is our entire
culture different?

00:52:10.600 --> 00:52:13.460
Start throwing things out,
whatever you can come up with.

00:52:13.460 --> 00:52:16.651
Are there nets over every house?

00:52:16.651 --> 00:52:18.400
Are houses designed
more like boats, where

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:21.240
everything is locked down?

00:52:21.240 --> 00:52:25.209
Are children sort of tied to
their beds before 7:00 PM?

00:52:25.209 --> 00:52:27.000
How do teenagers play
around with this, how

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:28.374
do they rebel,
given this, how do

00:52:28.374 --> 00:52:30.240
they get in trouble given this?

00:52:30.240 --> 00:52:32.657
How do people throw
nighttime parties?

00:52:32.657 --> 00:52:33.990
What does Burning Man look like?

00:52:37.380 --> 00:52:40.260
You could just keep asking
yourself this, over and over

00:52:40.260 --> 00:52:42.180
again, and it seems
silly, but really it's

00:52:42.180 --> 00:52:45.210
coming out of the tradition
of thought experiments,

00:52:45.210 --> 00:52:47.430
which Einstein uses.

00:52:47.430 --> 00:52:49.900
Just playing out what is
possible in the universe,

00:52:49.900 --> 00:52:50.955
what might occur.

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:58.550
And one last one I'll show
you, the very end is, so this--

00:52:58.550 --> 00:53:00.780
whoops.

00:53:00.780 --> 00:53:02.580
Yeah, this is the
world's most boring video

00:53:02.580 --> 00:53:05.310
unless you put
this music over it.

00:53:05.310 --> 00:53:08.880
Now all of a sudden
there's tension.

00:53:08.880 --> 00:53:12.030
And you're probably wondering,
did I put a shark in it?

00:53:12.030 --> 00:53:13.530
Is there-- is it
going to pop up?

00:53:13.530 --> 00:53:15.680
Are you going to see
that fin come up?

00:53:15.680 --> 00:53:17.820
Or is it just the
mouth going to pop up?

00:53:17.820 --> 00:53:19.740
I don't have those
skills, this is just

00:53:19.740 --> 00:53:21.480
like the world's
most boring clouds

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:23.760
out the window of an airplane.

00:53:23.760 --> 00:53:26.070
But we put the music on,
and suddenly your brain's

00:53:26.070 --> 00:53:27.670
creating a whole universe.

00:53:27.670 --> 00:53:31.006
You can do this with any
